<font color="#FF0000">RESPONSE TO ARTHUR</font><br>
<tt>Mon Apr 21  2:43:29 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Arthur,<br>
     Sometimes we create our own little hell, and carry it around with us. We may keep it bottled up inside, or vent it out at others, but often find it hard to deal with the underlying problem(s). While I've been rather fortunate in my Vietnam experience; I've gone through a few dark nights of the soul due to other things, some of my own making. Have been learning over the past 10 years, that failure or procrastination in dealing with one's own problems just doesn't affect oneself alone. Family, friends, co-workers, all catch some fallout.<br><br>
     I remember a friend from a prayer group asking me once after I'd been involved about 12 years if I had it all together yet. I told him no way, I'm still working on it. Another 10 years down the pike, and I'm still working on things I learned needed work in Vietnam or shortly after. Am still learning that the people placed in your path help you grow whether they're friendly and supportive or not. A person needs a balance of both silent reflection and constructive engagment with others.<br><br>
     From what you post; I think you're doing fine.<br>
                                 Gerry
<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


